Loading the .tif files of the Bioclim variables as downloaded from the WorldClim website (bio 30s; https://www.worldclim.org/data/worldclim21.html):

env_world <- list.files(path = "./", pattern = "-world-30sec.tif", all.files=TRUE, full.names=FALSE)
env_world <- stack(paste0("./", env_world))
plot(env_world)

Import the shapefile of Italy (our study area in the practical) as retrieved from https://www.diva-gis.org/gdata:

ita  <- readOGR(dsn = "./ITA_adm0.shp")
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "C:\Users\vajan\Desktop\Managing Bioclim rasters\ITA_adm0.shp", layer: "ITA_adm0"
## with 1 features
## It has 70 fields
## Integer64 fields read as strings:  ID_0 OBJECTID_1
plot(ita)

Crop the extent of the world raster objects to the one of the shapefile of Italy:

env_ita <- crop(env_world, ita)

Renaming the raster objects included in the object named âenv_itaâ with new names:

names(env_ita) <- c("BIO01", "BIO02", "BIO03", "BIO04", "BIO05", "BIO06", "BIO07",
                    "BIO08", "BIO09", "BIO10", "BIO11", "BIO12", "BIO13", "BIO14",
                    "BIO15", "BIO16", "BIO17", "BIO18", "BIO19", "ELEV")
plot(env_ita)

Mask the new raster objects to Italy only:

env_ita <- mask(env_ita, ita, inverse=F)
plot(env_ita)

Print the raster files in the working directory:

for(i in 1:dim(env_ita)[3]) {
  writeRaster(env_ita[[i]], filename=names(env_ita[[i]]), format="GTiff", overwrite=TRUE)
}
